ng -- tThe ʿAḳedah, Binding of Isaac, and Shoah Enigmas -- tThe Language of Lament: Unlocking the Potentials of Biblical Despair -- tDeath and Dying in the Qurʾan -- tThe Book of Job and Romantic Theodicy -- tSuicide and Compassion in Judaic Writings -- tPart V: Life & Humor -- tIntroduction to Life & Humor -- tDivine immanence and the realized liturgical eschatological vision in sūrat al-Fatḥ (Q 48) -- tExcess and Deficiency: Troubling Over Wealth and Discipleship in Luke-Acts -- t“Cursed be Haman?”: Haman as a Victim in the 14th Century Parody Massekheth Purim -- tEthnicity, Miracle, and Lepers in Luke: Inner Texture Analysis Of Luke 17:11–19 -- tFigurations of the Hierarchy for Life and Death in the Letters of Paul -- tPart VI: Crime & Punishment -- tIntroduction to Crime & Disobedience -- tThe Impact of Crime on Communities: A Conversation Between Biblical and Rabbinic Sources -- tHagioprepēs: The Rationalizing of Saintly Sin and Atrocities -- t“Let Every Person Be Subject”: The Reception of Romans 13 in Modern Biblical Studies and Theology -- t(Letaʿarafu لتعا رفو(ا , “ That you may Know one Another”: The Qurʾan as an Intertext in the Works of Mohja Kahf -- tContributors -- tIndex of Scriptures -- tGeneral Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAbrahamic scriptures serve as cultural pharmakon, prescribing what can act as both poison and remedy. This collection shows that their sometimes veiled but eternally powerful polemics can both destroy and build, exclude and include, and serve as the ultimate justification for cruelty or compassion. Here, scholars not only excavate these works for their formative and continuing cultural impact on communities, identities, and belief systems, they select some of the most troubling topics that global communities continue to navigate. Their analysis of both texts and their reception help explain how these texts promote norms and build collective identities. Rejecting the notion of the sacred realm as separate from the mundane realm and beyond critical challenge, this collection argues—both implicitly and sometimes transparently—for the presence of the sacred within everyday life and open to challenge. The very rituals, prayers, and traditions that are deemed sacred interweave into our cultural systems in infinite ways. Together, these authors explore the dynamic nature of everyday life and the often-brutal power of these texts over everyday meaning.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aSacred booksxHistory and criticism. 4aHebräische Bibel. 4aKoran. 4abanal. 4aheilig. 7aRELIGION / Comparative Religion.2bisacsh  aHebrew Bible.  aNew Testament, Qur'an.  aintertextuality.1 aAboagye Aryeh, Daniel Nii, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAhmad Saleh, Walid, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAli, Kecia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAmin, Taira, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAvants, Sophia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarbee, David M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCohen, Roni, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCorrigan, Sarah Katerina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDanner, Kerry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavis, Andrew R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDunning, Benjamin H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aD’Avila, Leonardo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEl-Badawi, Emran, econtributor.4ctb4https:/